    Explanation — what this Razor file does

Short answer: this is an About Razor view (server-side rendered) that 
sets the page title, reads the app assembly version, and renders a simple 
About page with Bootstrap classes, contact mailto link, a 
last-updated date, and the app version.

Below I’ll walk through it line-by-line, explain how Razor code runs, 
point out small behaviors you might not expect, and finish with 
a few practical improvements you can use.

Line-by-line
@using System.Reflection


Brings the System.Reflection namespace into scope for this view so 
you can call Assembly methods without fully qualifying them.

@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "About";
    var version = Assembly.GetEntryAssembly()?.GetName().Version?.ToString() ?? "n/a";
}


This is a Razor code block (@{ ... }) that runs on the server 
when the view is rendered.

ViewData["Title"] = "About"; — puts a value into the ViewData dictionary. 
Many layouts read ViewData["Title"] to set the <title> element in the page header.

var version = Assembly.GetEntryAssembly()?.GetName().Version?.ToString() ?? "n/a"; 
— attempts to read the app assembly version string:

Assembly.GetEntryAssembly() returns the entry assembly 
(usually the executable assembly).

.GetName().Version returns the Version (e.g., 1.0.0.0) set in the assembly metadata.

?.ToString() ?? "n/a": if any step is null, use "n/a" as fallback.

